<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-12-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-12-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="301" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d301">
                    <head>No. 301.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Phelps</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-12-08"><hi rend="italic">December</hi> 8,
                            1886</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 470.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to instruction No. 466, of the
                        7th instant, concerning the case of the American fishing schooner <hi rend="italic">Molly Adams</hi>, I now transmit to you herewith, for your
                        further information, a copy of the letter<note n="*" xml:id="d301fn1">Printed <ref target="frus1886#pg_429">pages 429</ref>, <ref target="frus1886#pg_430">430, Foreign Relations, 1886</ref>.</note>
                        of Mr. Solomon Jacobs, of the 12th ultimo, in which the matter was brought
                        to the attention of the Department.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. BAYARD.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>